docs.abstract: Statues and monuments that have long honored racist figures are being boxed up, spray-painted — or beheaded.
docs.snippet: Statues and monuments that have long honored racist figures are being boxed up, spray-painted — or beheaded.
docs.lead_paragraph: The statues have stood for more than a century in some places. Some are cast in bronze, others carved in stone. And all over the world, as protests against racism and police violence have renewed attention on legacies of injustices, people have been asking: Does this statue still need to be here?

headline.main: How Statues Are Falling Around the World
headline.print_headline: Dumped, Painted, Toppled, Boxed Up and Hoisted Away

docs.abstract: The pianist and “Late Show” bandleader has been bringing musical wake-up calls to events across New York.
docs.snippet: The pianist and “Late Show” bandleader has been bringing musical wake-up calls to events across New York.
docs.lead_paragraph: Jon Batiste, the jazz pianist and “The Late Show With Stephen Colbert” bandleader, has spent the last three weekends marching in the streets of New York, leading musicians and protesters through hymns and songs like “We Shall Overcome” and “Down by the Riverside.” Those without a horn or drum sing and, at Mr. Batiste’s exhortation, say their names: George Floyd. Breonna Taylor. And many others.

headline.main: Jazz Is Built for Protests. Jon Batiste Is Taking It to the Streets.
